LAGOS – President Muhammadu Buhari on Tuesday charged the Independent National Electoral Commission (INEC) and the Nigeria Police to ensure that future elections in the country are held under a violence-free atmosphere. The president made this disclosure after he met with the INEC Chairman, Prof. Mahmood Yakubu and the Inspector General of Police, Mohammed Adamu at the State House in Abuja. President Buhari, who stated that he was determined to give Nigeria an electoral system that meets with best practices anywhere in the world, also charged the electoral umpire to stick to the rules of fair play and adherence to justice. Powered by RubiQube Ad Network According to him, “Those that you declare as winners must be the candidates that the people have chosen. Democracy is about free will, and the will of the people must be allowed to prevail. Get your acts right, and leave no room for underhand tricks or manipulation.” Speaking further, the president maintained that in achieving this, the police have a very big role to play, as it is their responsibility to ensure that elections are done in an atmosphere that is devoid of violence. He said: “Our elections must be done in violence-free atmosphere. The process must be free, fair, decent, devoid of intimidation or malpractices. It is the duty of the police to accomplish that, and it is what I expect in the elections immediately ahead, and going forward.”